outcomes.title: Limits of special transcendental functions
outcomes.description: I can compute limits of special transcendental functions.
outcomes.template:
Sketch graphs to compute the limits below.

\lim_{ {{v1}} \to 0 } \frac{ {{L1_num}} }{ {{v1}} }

\lim_{ {{v2}} \to 0 } \frac{ {{L2_num}} }{ {{v2}} }

{{L1}}

{{L2}}

Use a calculator and a table of values to estimate the value of the limit below correctly to three decimal places. Since the limit is "two-sided", make sure your table accounts for {{v3}} \to 0^+ and {{v3}} \to 0^-.

\lim_{ {{v3}} \to 0 } \frac{ \left( {{b}} \right)^{ {{v3}} } - 1 }{ {{v3}} }

{{L3}}

outcomes.title: Limits with L'Hôpital's Rule
outcomes.description: I can compute limits using L'Hôpital's Rule when the initial form is indeterminate of type 0/0 or ∞/∞.
outcomes.template:
Compute the exact value for each of the limits below.

\lim_{x\to 0} \frac { {{Z1}} \left( 1-\cos^{ {{p1}} }(x) \right) } { {{denom1}} }

{{ans1}}

\lim_{x\to \infty} \frac { {{num2}} } { {{denom2}} }

{{ans2}}

outcomes.title: The definition of derivative
outcomes.description: I can use the definition of the derivative as a limit and knowledge of special transcendental functions to compute derivatives of sin(x) and cos(x).
outcomes.template:
Let f(x) = {{f}}. Use the definition of the derivative as a limit and your knowledge of some special trigonometric limits (see the LSTr outcome) to prove that

f'(x) = {{df}}

f'(x) = \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{ f(x+h) - f(x) }{h} = [\text{ ... insert your proof here ... }] = {{df}}

outcomes.title: Derivatives of trigonometric functions
outcomes.description: I can use the quotient rule and knowledge of sin(x) and cos(x) to compute derivatives of sec(x), csc(x), tan(x), and cot(x).
outcomes.template:
First, recall the derivatives for the sine and cosine functions.

\frac{d}{dx}\sin(x) =

\frac{d}{dx}\cos(x) =

\frac{d}{dx}\sin(x) = \cos(x)

\frac{d}{dx}\cos(x) = -\sin(x)

Use your knowledge of trigonometric identities, the quotient rule, and the derivatives from the previous task to prove that

\frac{d}{dx} {{f}} = {{df}}

\frac{d}{dx} {{f}} = [\text{ ... insert your proof here ... }] = {{df}}
